18 : How DB Connection is Established
================================================================================

When application ko database connection chahiye hota hai:

    1. Application DB operation trigger karti hai.

        Example:

            userRepository.findById(1L);

        Ye call Spring Data JPA repository se start hoti hai.

    2. Spring Data JPA request Hibernate ko delegate karta hai.

        Hibernate repository method / JPQL ko SQL query me convert karta hai.

        Example SQL:

            SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = 1;

    3. Hibernate JDBC API ke through DB operation perform karta hai.

        Hibernate ko query execute karne ke liye JDBC Connection chahiye hota hai.

        Spring Boot me connection usually DataSource se milta hai.

        Internally:

            dataSource.getConnection();

        Important:

            Spring Boot me ye DataSource generally HikariCP-backed hota hai.

            HikariCP ek connection pool hai.

        If pool me available connection hai:

            HikariCP existing JDBC Connection return kar deta hai.

        If pool me connection available nahi hai
        and maximum pool size cross nahi hua:

            HikariCP JDBC Driver ka use karke new physical DB connection create karta hai.

        Plain JDBC me connection directly aise create kar sakte hain:

            DriverManager.getConnection(url, username, password);

        But Spring Boot applications me usually HikariCP ke through connection milta hai.

    4. JDBC Driver JDBC URL parse karta hai.

        Example:

            jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/testdb

        Driver ko milta hai:

            Host     = localhost
            Port     = 3306
            Database = testdb

    5. JDBC Driver database server ke host and port par TCP connection open karta hai.

        TCP handshake hota hai:

            SYN
            SYN-ACK
            ACK

        Iske baad application server aur database server ke beech
        network connection ready ho jaata hai.

    6. Agar SSL/TLS enabled hai, to TLS handshake hota hai.

        TLS ke baad connection encrypted ho jaata hai.

    7. Database-specific handshake hota hai.

        MySQL server JDBC Driver ko initial handshake packet bhejta hai.

        Is packet me hota hai:

            - server/protocol version
            - supported capabilities
            - authentication method
            - SSL support
            - random challenge/salt

    8. JDBC Driver handshake read karke authentication response bhejta hai.

        Driver decide karta hai:

            - protocol compatible hai ya nahi
            - SSL use karna hai ya nahi
            - kaunsa auth method use karna hai
            - kaunsi capabilities enable karni hain

        Then driver database server ko bhejta hai:

            - username
            - selected database
            - client capabilities
            - authentication response/password token

        Note:

            Usually password plain text me directly nahi bheja jaata.
            Server ke challenge/salt ke basis par secure auth response bheja jaata hai.

    9. Database server credentials and permissions validate karta hai.

        Server check karta hai:

            - username/password correct hai ya nahi
            - database access allowed hai ya nahi
            - given host se connect karne ki permission hai ya nahi

    10. Authentication successful hone ke baad DB session create hota hai.

        DB session server-side logical context hota hai.

        Isme maintain ho sakta hai:

            - authenticated user
            - selected database/schema
            - transaction state
            - session variables
            - connection-specific state

        Database server required memory/resources bhi allocate karta hai.

    11. Connection ready ho jaata hai.

        Ab application SQL queries send kar sakti hai.

